  "prompt": "How do I find an engine for an SAE Supra?",
  "response": "Finding an engine for an SAE (Society of Automotive Engineers) Suprace team involves careful planning, research, and networking. The SAE Supra competition involves designing, building, and racing a formula-style car, and the engine is a critical component. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you find the right engine:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Understand the Competition Rules**\n   - Review the SAE Supra rulebook thoroughly to understand the engine requirements, restrictions, and guidelines.\n   - Pay attention to engine displacement limits, fuel type (gasoline, electric, hybrid, etc.), and any specific regulations.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Define Your Team\u2019s Goals**\n   - Decide whether you want a purpose-built engine, a modified production engine, or an off-the-shelf solution.\n   - Consider factors like budget, performance, reliability, and ease of integration.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Research and Shortlist Engine Options**\n   - **Motorcycle Engines**: Commonly used due to their high power-to-weight ratio and compact size (e.g., Honda CBR600RR, Yamaha R6, Kawasaki Ninja).\n   - **Small Car Engines**: Engines from compact cars like the Suzuki Swift or Honda Civic can be a good fit.\n   - **Electric Powertrains**: If your team is exploring electric vehicles (EVs), research electric motors and battery systems.\n   - **Custom-Built Engines**: Some teams design and build their own engines, but this requires significant expertise and resources.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Contact Manufacturers and Suppliers**\n   - Reach out to engine manufacturers, distributors, or suppliers to inquire about availability, pricing, and technical specifications.\n   - Look for companies that are open to sponsoring student projects, as they may offer discounts or donations.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Explore Sponsorships and Donations**\n   - Many teams secure engines through sponsorships or donations from companies in the automotive or motorsport industry.\n   - Prepare a professional sponsorship proposal highlighting your team\u2019s goals, the benefits of partnering with you, and how the sponsor will be recognized.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Consider Used or Rebuilt Engines**\n   - Check online marketplaces, salvage yards, or auctions for used engines that meet your requirements.\n   - Rebuilt or refurbished engines can be a cost-effective option, but ensure they are in good working condition.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Network with Other Teams**\n   - Connect with other SAE Supra teams to learn about their engine choices and sourcing strategies.\n   - Attend SAE events, competitions, or conferences to build relationships with industry professionals and other students.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Evaluate Integration and Compatibility**\n   - Ensure the engine can be easily integrated into your car\u2019s design and meets your team\u2019s performance goals.\n   - Consider the availability of spare parts, tuning options, and technical support.\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Plan for Testing and Tuning**\n   - Once you\u2019ve secured an engine, plan for thorough testing and tuning to optimize its performance for the competition.\n\n---\n\n### 10. **Document and Share Your Progress**\n   - Keep detailed records of your engine selection process, modifications, and testing results.\n   - Share your findings with your team and the SAE Supra community to contribute to collective knowledge.\n\n---\n\n### Resources to Help You:\n   - **SAE International Website**: [www.sae.org](https://www.sae.org)\n   - **Online Communities**: SAE forums, Reddit (e.g., r/SAE), and Facebook groups.\n   - **Local Motorsport Clubs**: Reach out to local racing teams or clubs for advice and potential leads.\n\nBy following these steps and leveraging your team\u2019s creativity and resourcefulness, you should be able to find a suitable engine for your SAE Supra project. Good luck!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
